  "text": "The similarity of protein sequences of CheA, CheB, CheC, CheD, CheR, CheV, CheW, CheY, McpA, McpB, and McpC of organisms related to B. subtilis were compared to the reference organism B. amyloliquefaciens FZB42. They showed variability on the level of 55% to 99% identity, as detailed in Fig. 1 . B. amyloliquefaciens chemotaxis proteins were most similar to their counterparts from B. subtilis 168, followed by B. licheniformis ATCC14580, then B. pumilus SAFR032. The level of similarity between B. subtilis and B. amyloliquefaciens was above 65% for all homologous proteins, indicating a high level of conservation. However, recognizable variations in proteins were discovered between subspecies B. amyloliquefaciens and B. subtilis. The frequency of amino acid substitutions in chemotaxis proteins on average was the same as or a little bit higher than in the gyrase A (GyrA) subunit (data not shown) broadly used for phylogenetic inferences [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . A general belief is that GyrA accumulates amino acid substitutions in a random molecular clock fashion without any significant evolutionary pressure.",
